TITLE: Accessing Frontend Cache Instruction in Early Middleware in TYPO3
DESCRIPTION: This code demonstrates how to safely access and modify the frontend cache instruction in an early middleware before the typo3/cms-frontend/tsfe middleware is executed. It shows proper null coalescing to handle cases where the attribute might not exist yet.
SOURCE: https://github.com/TYPO3-Documentation/TYPO3CMS-Reference-CoreApi/blob/main/Documentation/ApiOverview/RequestLifeCycle/RequestAttributes/FrontendCacheInstruction.rst#2025-04-16_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: php
CODE:
```
<?php
declare(strict_types=1);

namespace MyVendor\MyExtension\Middleware;

use Psr\Http\Message\ResponseInterface;
use Psr\Http\Message\ServerRequestInterface;
use Psr\Http\Server\MiddlewareInterface;
use Psr\Http\Server\RequestHandlerInterface;
use TYPO3\CMS\Frontend\Cache\CacheInstruction;

final class MyEarlyMiddleware implements MiddlewareInterface
{
    public function process(ServerRequestInterface $request, RequestHandlerInterface $handler): ResponseInterface
    {
        // Get instruction. The attribute may not exist yet in early middlewares.
        // Thus, create an empty instruction if none exists.
        $cacheInstruction = $request->getAttribute('frontend.cache.instruction') ?? new CacheInstruction();
        // Force caching being disabled:
        $cacheInstruction = $cacheInstruction->withDisabledCache();
        // OR re-enable caching, which is actually the default when creating a new instruction:
        // $cacheInstruction = $cacheInstruction->withEnabledCache();
        // Set the result back to the request
        $request = $request->withAttribute('frontend.cache.instruction', $cacheInstruction);
        return $handler->handle($request);
    }
}
```

